										<li id="comment-113239" class="commentbody"><div class="commenthead"><img alt='apotheon`s avatar' src='http://univacc.net/avatar.png' class='avatar avatar-32 photo' height='32' width='32' />								<div class="commentcount">60</div>
								<span class="authorlink"><a href='http://univacc.net' class='url'>apotheon</a></span>&nbsp;								<span class=""></span>
													<br />
								<a class="commentlink" href="#comment-113239" title="">Sunday, 22 March 2015</a>
							</div>
						<p>I think you mean "OpenPGP Contract", not "GPG Contract".  Once upon a time, there was PGP, whose operational model was ultimately codified in the OpenPGP protocol.  Both the modern PGP tools and GnuPG (aka GPG) are implementations of OpenPGP.  We also have OpenPGP::SDK, CalcCrypto OpenPGP, KryptoKit PGP Chrome Extension, the half-built netpgp (which might still fork and finish), and several other implementations floating around.  They should all be able to participate, mutually compatibly, in the same cryptocontract culture, with no two contractors necessarily using the same implementation.</p>
<p>In fact, I rather suspect that GPG will fade away as other implementations gain currency.  It's old, crusty, built from barely readable source code, license terms inhibited, and maintained by people with a pathologically difficult attitude toward various important software development philosophy (e.g. API and UI design).</p>
						</li>

										<li id="comment-113240" class="adminbody"><div class="adminhead"><img alt='Mircea Popescu`s avatar' src='http://trilema.com/avatar.png' class='avatar avatar-32 photo' height='32' width='32' />								<div class="commentcount">61</div>
